–Female":"1104–Overleden","about 1140":"circa 1140","about 1182":"circa 1182","1104":"1104","1268":"1268","1100":"1100","1144":"1144","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1140–":"about 1140–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1144–Female":"1144–Deceased","1182–Male":"1182–Deceased","1170–Male":"1170–Deceased","1180–Male":"1180–Deceased","1184–Male":"1184–Deceased","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1104–Female":"1104–Deceased","about 1140":"about 1140","about 1182":"about 1182","1104":"1104","1268":"1268","1100":"1100","1144":"1144","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Caeo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hispanic: unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dafydd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>David</b> . In widespread use during the Middle Ages, it was later largely replaced by the English form, but since the late 19th century it has come into its own again."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dafydd ap Maredudd, of Caeo was born about 1140, in Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Maredudd Hen, was 42 and his mother, Mrs. Maredudd Hen, was 38. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Dafydd ap Maredudd of Caeo."},"et":{"about 1140–":"umbes 1140–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1144–Female":"1144–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1184–Male":"1184–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","about 1182":"umbes 1182","1104":"1104","1268":"1268","1100":"1100","1144":"1144","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1140–":"noin 1140–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1268–Female":"1268–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1144–Female":"1144–Kuollut","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1184–Male":"1184–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","about 1140":"noin 1140","about 1182":"noin 1182","1104":"1104","1268":"1268","1100":"1100","1144":"1144","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1140–":"environ 1140–Décé